  🧠 The[0m[2m results[0m[2m from[0m[2m the previous[0m[2m run are[0m[2m significant[0m[2m. The[0m[2m race[0m[2m condition in[0m[2m `de[0m[2mqueue`[0m[2m is more[0m[2m aggressive[0m[2m than I[0m[2m initially thought[0m[2m. Because[0m[2m the[0m[2m check[0m[2m for[0m[2m `pending[0m[2m` status[0m[2m and the[0m[2m update to[0m[2m `processing[0m[2m` are[0m[2m separated[0m[2m by an[0m[2m `await[0m[2m asyncio.sleep[0m[2m(0[0m[2m.01[0m[2m)`, every[0m[2m single[0m[2m worker sees[0m[2m the same[0m[2m job as[0m[2m available[0m[2m before[0m[2m anyone[0m[2m claims[0m[2m it.[0m[2m This is[0m[2m why we[0m[2m see `[[0m[2mWorker[0m[2m 0]`[0m[2m through[0m[2m `[Worker[0m[2m 4[0m[2m]` all[0m[2m picking up[0m[2m job[0m[2m 1[0m[2m.[0m[2m The[0m[2m `sleep[0m[2m` is[0m[2m meant[0m[2m to simulate[0m[2m I[0m[2m/O,[0m[2m but in[0m[2m an[0m[2m async context[0m[2m, it[0m[2m creates[0m[2m a gap[0m[2m where other[0m[2m cor[0m[2moutines run[0m[2m.[0m[2m
     
     Wait[0m[2m, there's[0m[2m a[0m[2m second problem[0m[2m here[0m[2m. The[0m[2m '[0m[2mvan[0m[2mishing failures[0m[2m' part[0m[2m of[0m[2m the issue[0m[2m is obvious[0m[2m in[0m[2m the logs[0m[2m. When[0m[2m an exception[0m[2m occurs[0m[2m—even[0m[2m a[0m[2m simulated one[0m[2m—the[0m[2m `except[0m[2m` block[0m[2m in `[0m[2mprocess[0m[2m_job`[0m[2m prints[0m[2m a[0m[2m message,[0m[2m but it[0m[2m never[0m[2m actually[0m[2m updates[0m[2m the queue[0m[2m.[0m[2m The job[0m[2m remains stuck[0m[2m in the[0m[2m `processing[0m[2m` state[0m[2m instead[0m[2m of transitioning[0m[2m to `[0m[2mfailed`[0m[2m or being[0m[2m res[0m[2mcheduled.[0m[2m
     
